I had to do something similar for an app I'm working on, and ended up with something like this:

```python
import sys
import clip

app = clip.App()

@app.main()
def f():
	pass

@f.subcommand()
def x():
	print('Invoked x!')

try:
	app.run(sys.argv[1:] or '-h')  # If no arguments, pass in -h for help text
except clip.ClipExit:
	pass
```

Understandably this is not ideal, so I'll try to figure out a way to make it easier. Several ideas:

1. Pass the Command in to the decorated function if necessary, sort of like Click's [`@click.pass_context`](http://click.pocoo.org/3/commands/#nested-handling-and-contexts), so you can do e.g. `this.help()` from within `f()`.
2. Have a global `app.help()`. The issue here is that commands are still invoked before their subcommands, so calling this will always short-circuit the program.

Any thoughts/feedback is welcome.

