with this, if you do not see any contraindication (ex: reserved attributes with one underscore)

```python
    if params._values.id:
        for row in entity.rows:
            if row.id == params._values.id:
                id = params._values.id
                _update_row(row, params)
                row.update(params._values)
```

Similarly to the JavaScript version of this code, I like to use the parenthesis-style only when I need to use the variables:

```
// javascript
app.schemas[params.schema].entities[params.entity].properties;

# python
js_schemas[params.schema].entities[params.entity].properties
```

