@suoto The Python side of VUnit is not integrated with the VHDL logging mechanism in any way today. The Python side just blindly captures what is printed to stdout/stderr during simulation. If you in VHDL choose to write a log-file to a csv file using the log package it just becomes a csv file on disk that the Python part does not know or care about.

Adding a general output filter somewhere in the simulator independent parts of the Python code that detected lines with error or warning words in them for coloring would be the easiest solution. It would be unintelligent though since it cannot now the intention of the line being printed such as if it really was a warning or just contained the word warning.

NOTE: Your initial VHDL-based solution will not work on Windows without using Cygwin or similar since the Windows console does not use in-stream escape characters to change color but rather a Win32 API.

