@soupault @b52 Oops, this response has been sitting in an open tab for the past couple of days:

I agree with @b52 that `True` is not a good default value — it's a little too active/prescriptive. In the past, when we have tried to do such "good defaults", we've often gotten into trouble (e.g. sigma=1 and convert2lab=True for SLIC) and had to backtrack on the API. I think the worst case behaviour is better for do-nothing defaults — people who want the advanced behaviour can find it, otherwise the function does what it says it does and nothing more.

Having said that, I suggest a default of `False` (assuming we want to keep the bool option), as it reads a little better than 0. And yes, the documentation should definitely mention what bool options do.

@GGoussar regarding tests, especially for those new to unit testing, I recommend imitation. Take a look at any `tests` subdirectory: you'll find a number of files names `test_*.py` containing functions with a `test_` prefix. 

Copy the style. Copy the footer `if __main__:` and NumPy imports at the top. Then look at how things are done. Basically the test functions should efficiently run a given algorithm several ways, enough to "cover" every line of executing code. If a result is obtained, it should be compared against a known good result or manually calculated array. Sometimes these are hardcoded, sometimes arrived at via alternative algorithm path. Array comparisons are generally done with `np.allclose`. *Tests do not need a `return` statement; they should return nothing (technically `None`) unless they fail*.

Sometimes you need to check for expected errors, which can also be done. Search the repo for uses of `assert_raises`.

